WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.160
[Amit Varma]: Arthur C. Clarke once said, quote, any sufficiently advanced technology is indistinguishable from

00:00:10.160 --> 00:00:15.280
[Amit Varma]: magic, stop quote. If someone from say 1981 travelled all the way to 2021, this world

00:00:15.280 --> 00:00:19.840
[Amit Varma]: would look magical. I suppose every generation feels that the world has changed so much in

00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:24.760
[Amit Varma]: its time. But this is more true of our generation than any other. Technology has made the pace

00:00:24.760 --> 00:00:29.200
[Amit Varma]: of change almost exponential over the last few decades. A friend of mine once remarked

00:00:29.200 --> 00:00:34.240
[Amit Varma]: that kids today may never know what it is to be lost, physically lost. All hail GPS

00:00:34.240 --> 00:00:38.960
[Amit Varma]: and the internet. When I was a kid, we would struggle to get hold of books and films and

00:00:38.960 --> 00:00:44.800
[Amit Varma]: music that we wanted. Our life was a series of lost counterfactuals, things we did not

00:00:44.800 --> 00:00:49.520
[Amit Varma]: discover because we were in a bubble, journeys we could not take or even conceive of. All

00:00:49.520 --> 00:00:54.280
[Amit Varma]: that has changed so much. And here in the second half of my 40s, I sometimes find myself

00:00:54.280 --> 00:00:59.160
[Amit Varma]: taking this change for granted. What I would have found magical yesterday is commonplace

00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:03.640
[Amit Varma]: today. And I think it makes sense to sometimes sit back and take stock. This is especially

00:01:03.640 --> 00:01:08.320
[Amit Varma]: so in India, where so much has changed. And so much has also not changed. Some of the

00:01:08.320 --> 00:01:12.920
[Amit Varma]: change is superficial, some of it is deep and fundamental. Our lives have changed, our

00:01:12.920 --> 00:01:17.960
[Amit Varma]: society has changed, our politics has changed. And what better way to consider all of this

00:01:17.960 --> 00:01:22.560
[Amit Varma]: than through the life of someone whose main preoccupation for more than 40 years has been

00:01:22.560 --> 00:01:31.160
[Amit Varma]: to document and make sense of the present moment. There's a lot to learn from that journey.

00:01:31.160 --> 00:01:36.360
[Unknown]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioral

00:01:36.360 --> 00:01:43.640
[Amit Varma]: science. Please welcome your host, Amit Varma.

00:01:43.640 --> 00:01:47.520
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to the scene and the unseen. My guest today is Veer Sanghvi, one of the giants of

00:01:47.520 --> 00:01:52.200
[Amit Varma]: Indian journalism. He became an editor in his 20s around 40 years ago and shaped what

00:01:52.200 --> 00:01:57.040
[Amit Varma]: I thought was the finest news magazine of my growing up years called Sunday. He would

00:01:57.040 --> 00:02:01.280
[Amit Varma]: go on to be a pioneer in Indian television as well. And he also edited the Hindustan

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:06.080
[Amit Varma]: Times for a few years and brought it kicking and screaming into the 21st century. He can

00:02:06.080 --> 00:02:10.800
[Amit Varma]: write about food, politics and society with equal ease. But in all these years, his gaze

00:02:10.800 --> 00:02:16.440
[Amit Varma]: has mostly gone outwards. Until now. Veer has just come out with a memoir called A Rude

00:02:16.440 --> 00:02:21.600
[Amit Varma]: Life and I love reading it. I've admired his clear lucid prose since the early 1990s. But

00:02:21.600 --> 00:02:27.160
[Amit Varma]: the one thing that surprised me about this book is the humor. It's sharp, witty and self-reflective

00:02:27.160 --> 00:02:31.440
[Amit Varma]: and I found myself laughing out loud throughout the book. But this book does much more than

00:02:31.440 --> 00:02:36.500
[Amit Varma]: just make us laugh. It also gives us a sense of the times and is especially acute when

00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:40.480
[Amit Varma]: it comes to understanding Indian politics. I loved having this conversation. But before

00:02:40.480 --> 00:02:45.560
[Amit Varma]: we get to it, let's take a quick commercial break.

00:02:45.560 --> 00:02:49.920
[Amit Varma]: How well do I know myself? Not as well as I used to think I do. We sometimes realize

00:02:49.920 --> 00:02:54.320
[Amit Varma]: the extent to which other people are a mystery to us. But we underestimate how much we are

00:02:54.320 --> 00:02:58.960
[Amit Varma]: a mystery to ourselves. We often imagine that we are blank slates. But that's not true.

00:02:58.960 --> 00:03:04.080
[Amit Varma]: We are shaped and constrained by our genes. And understanding the way we are wired can

00:03:04.080 --> 00:03:08.520
[Amit Varma]: help us make the most of them. And one way towards this self-knowledge comes from the

00:03:08.520 --> 00:03:13.920
[Amit Varma]: sponsors of this episode, MapMyGenome. 20 years ago, sequencing your genome could cost

00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:19.120
[Amit Varma]: around $20 million. Today, MapMyGenome can sequence your genes and give you a genome

00:03:19.120 --> 00:03:24.240
[Amit Varma]: number 3, as it were, for just a few thousand rupees. You only need to get tested once,

